arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
Daily Trench Journal

Area F, Trench 7

May 25, 2005

C. Painter

Today excavation continued in fill L7151 along the south baulk, first removing the 10 cm remaining from yesterdayâ€™s work, then digging 10 cm more across the entire southern strip of the locus with small hand picks. In the southwest corner of L7151 ashy inclusions are beginning to emerge signaling the top of pit L7146 as it continues east into this locus. Also a cluster of complete pedestalled bowls (KT9, 10) was recovered from L7151 and were found cutting into surface 7159, not sitting on the surface.

In total, 20 cm was excavated in 7156 with small hand picks where in the southeast corner of the locus another trampled pebble surface is beginning to emerge below what can now be considered suprasurface fill 7156. This surface will be traced in the coming days to see the extent and whether or not it is associated with any of the nearby mud brick walls (7157, 7158, 7160).

Small hand picks were also used in the 10 cm excavation and leveling in L7145. This was after burial L7150 was successfully removed. This burial proved to be extremely fragmentary and was essentially divided into two parts: a northern grouping of fragmentary unidentifiable bones most probably scattered by hand pick excavation in this area (thus nothing was found in situ) and a southern grouping which had an in situ grouping of long bones (arms?), fingers, and fragmentary shoulder blade. This latter group was found cutting the northern edge of wall 7160 and resting on what appears to be a white lime or mud plastered surface which is extremely fragmentary. It could also be mortar between courses for the mud brick wall.

The only work that was completed in 7153 was the removal of an in situ animal vertebra (KT5) and other associated animal bones. What became clear at the end of the day as small hand pick and trowel excavation was performed in L7155 was the appearance of a second mud brick wall in the northwest quadrant along with an ashy pit and possibly fill. New loci will need to be opened in this area tomorrow.
